<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-498-856  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 498 856.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>The Wall Street Journal  June 4 1990 pR28(W) pR28(E) 41 col in.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Computer confusion. (difficulties encountered when companies tryto automate) (Workplace of the Future supplement)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Carroll, Paul B.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Computers have produced many success stories, but companies thatwant to automate ought to consider some of the difficulties thathave been encountered as well.andP;  Consultants say that problemsoccur when corporate buyers do not think through all the issues.andO;Many buyers, for example, buy systems on the basis of price, butprice turns out to be only about 15 percent of total costs.andO;Training, which often gets little attention, sometimes is thebiggest cost.andP;  Companies often try to cut corners, buyingequipment that lacks essential features, but it is often morepractical to buy standard equipment or software that has standardfeatures, even if the initial cost might be more.andP;  Standardizationwithin a company and how to handle upgrading are other issues toconsider when purchasing computer products.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     AutomationOffice AutomationResistance to Computer TechnologyComputerphobiaPurchasesHardware SelectionSoftware SelectionEquipment Acquisition.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>